title: Empowering Designers for Better Software
preview:
many hot takes about design are born from how poorly the design practice of many software orgs is run.

the normal (and bad flow) is:
ether -> prod mng -> design -> eng -> users

design is not coming up with how things should look. design is determining how things should work.

one reason why so much software sucks, i.e. full of manipulative and useful features, is because we've let product managers have been making functionality choices. the role of the PM is to gather accurate, detailed information from the "business" and users and determine the prioritization of competing interests. This information is passed to designers who should be making the functionality choices.

i've long abhorred long product requirement docs because its clear the PM is taking on too much responsibility and making too choices. the PM should be able to clearly articulate the Job to be Done while the designers determine what will get it done. the designer than works in concert with engineering to get it done.

design is so much more important than many realize and our products suffer when designers are not given the control required to manifest high

many admire Apple and Airbnb, but few have the courage to prioritize design and empower their designers.

title: TypeScript Mem0
preview:
build a custom version of mem0 in typescript that can do all of this:
Mem0 (pronounced as "mem-zero") enhances AI assistants and agents with an intelligent memory layer, enabling personalized AI interactions. Mem0 remembers user preferences, adapts to individual needs, and continuously improves over time, making it ideal for customer support chatbots, AI assistants, and autonomous systems.

Features & Use Cases
Core Capabilities:

Multi-Level Memory: User, Session, and AI Agent memory retention with adaptive personalization
Developer-Friendly: Simple API integration, cross-platform consistency, and hassle-free managed service
Applications:

AI Assistants: Seamless conversations with context and personalization
Learning & Support: Tailored content recommendations and context-aware customer assistance
Healthcare & Companions: Patient history tracking and deeper relationship building
Productivity & Gaming: Streamlined workflows and adaptive environments based on user behavior
Get Started
Get started quickly with Mem0 Platform - our fully managed solution that provides automatic updates, advanced analytics, enterprise security, and dedicated support. Create a free account to begin.

For complete control, you can self-host Mem0 using our open-source package. See the Quickstart guide below to set up your own instance.

Quickstart Guide
Install the Mem0 package via pip:

pip install mem0ai
Basic Usage
Mem0 requires an LLM to function, with gpt-4o from OpenAI as the default. However, it supports a variety of LLMs; for details, refer to our Supported LLMs documentation.

First step is to instantiate the memory:

from openai import OpenAI
from mem0 import Memory

openai_client = OpenAI()
mem0 = Memory()

def chat_with_memories(message: str, user_id: str = "default_user") -> str:
    # Retrieve relevant memories
    relevant_memories = mem0.search(query=message, user_id=user_id, limit=3)
    memories_str = "\n".join(f"- {entry['memory']}" for entry in relevant_memories)
    
    # Generate Assistant response
    system_prompt = f"You are a helpful AI. Answer the question based on query and memories.\nUser Memories:\n{memories_str}"
    messages = [{"role": "system", "content": system_prompt}, {"role": "user", "content": message}]
    response = openai_client.chat.completions.create(model="gpt-4o-mini", messages=messages)
    assistant_response = response.choices[0].message.content

    # Create new memories from the conversation
    messages.append({"role": "assistant", "content": assistant_response})
    mem0.add(messages, user_id=user_id)

    return assistant_response

def main():
    print("Chat with AI (type 'exit' to quit)")
    while True:
        user_input = input("You: ").strip()
        if user_input.lower() == 'exit':
            print("Goodbye!")
            break
        print(f"AI: {chat_with_memories(user_input)}")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()

title: Understanding Business-Influencer-Consumer Relationships as ETL Processes
preview:
Understanding the Business-Influencer-Consumer Ecosystem as an ETL Process

In today’s fast-paced digital world, businesses and influencers work together to create compelling campaigns that drive consumer action. But have you ever wondered how this ecosystem functions? It turns out, the relationship between businesses, influencers, and consumers closely mirrors a data ETL (Extract, Transform, Load) process. Let’s break it down step-by-step and explore how the stages of this ecosystem align with ETL concepts.

1️⃣ Extract: Allocating Resources to Influencers

Just like data is extracted from raw sources in an ETL process, businesses start by allocating resources to influencers. These resources—such as products, services, and promotional budgets—serve as the “raw data” that will eventually be refined and delivered to the target audience. This initial allocation is crucial because it sets the stage for the influencer to work with the brand’s assets and communicate them to their followers.

2️⃣ Transform: Tailoring the Message for the Audience

In the ETL process, data is transformed to meet specific needs or formats. Similarly, influencers take the raw materials (products and messaging) provided by businesses and adapt them to suit the preferences of their unique audience. This step ensures that the message resonates on a personal level, increasing the chances of engagement. Whether it’s a product review, tutorial, or lifestyle integration, influencers work to transform the brand message into something authentic and relevant to their followers.

3️⃣ Load: Distributing Content to the Consumer

Once the message is transformed, it’s time to “load” it into the consumer’s environment. In ETL, this step involves loading the transformed data into a system where it can be accessed and utilized. In this ecosystem, the influencer distributes the tailored content across various platforms—social media, blogs, YouTube, etc.—making it available to consumers in a format that they can easily engage with. The “load” here isn’t just about grabbing attention; it’s about ensuring the content is delivered where consumers can interact with it meaningfully.

4️⃣ Action/Conversion: Turning Engagement into Sales

After the content has been loaded into the consumer’s environment, the next step is where things get interesting: the consumer takes action. In ETL, once the data is loaded, it’s used to inform decision-making or analysis. In this ecosystem, the action step is where consumer interest is converted into tangible outcomes, like purchases or further engagement with the product. Whether it’s buying the product, signing up for a service, or simply learning more, the goal is to drive a conversion—just as data is used to drive insights and decisions.

5️⃣ Iterate & Optimize: Refining the System for Better Results

In an ETL process, feedback and insights are constantly used to refine the extraction, transformation, and loading stages for greater efficiency and accuracy. Similarly, businesses and influencers regularly assess the effectiveness of their campaigns. They analyze engagement, sales data, and consumer feedback to optimize their strategies for future campaigns. By fine-tuning each stage of the process, they can achieve better results and create a more seamless ecosystem over time.

Conclusion

By looking at the Business-Influencer-Consumer ecosystem through the lens of an ETL process, we can better understand how each stage builds upon the previous one to drive meaningful results. From extracting resources to transforming messages and loading them into the consumer’s environment, this ecosystem operates much like a well-oiled data pipeline. The ultimate goal? Turning consumer attention into action, and continuously optimizing the system for even greater success.

In this data-driven world, the Business-Influencer-Consumer ecosystem is an ongoing cycle of engagement, conversion, and optimization—much like an ETL process that constantly adapts and improves based on feedback. Understanding this framework can help businesses and influencers create more effective, impactful campaigns that drive lasting consumer loyalty and growth.

preview:
based on the following PRD, create an LLM system prompt that will create similar structured PRDs for other product ideas:

## tl;dr


Build a set of features that allows users to personalize their news experience by selecting topics of interest and engaging with content through categories like Liked, Bookmarked, and Shared. This enhances user retention, increases time spent in the app, and boosts engagement.

## Problem Statement

Users often struggle to find relevant and interesting news in an increasingly crowded digital landscape. They need an intuitive way to personalize their news feed, save content for later, and interact with articles they enjoy. This feature will address these gaps and provide a more engaging and tailored news experience.

## Goals


### Business Goals

â€¢ Increase user engagement and time spent in the app by 15% within 3 months.

â€¢ Drive higher retention by delivering relevant content tailored to user interests.

â€¢ Create new monetization opportunities through targeted advertising or premium features tied to personalization.

  

### User Goals

â€¢ Easily select topics of interest to curate a personalized news feed.

â€¢ Save articles for later reading and quickly find them in a dedicated section.

â€¢ Express preferences (like, bookmark, share) to better manage their news consumption.

  

Non-Goals

â€¢ Building a full-fledged recommendation engine (future consideration).

â€¢ Enabling offline access to bookmarked content (out of scope for this iteration).

User Stories

1. As a user, I want to select topics of interest so that I can receive updates about subjects I care about.

2. As a user, I want to bookmark articles to read later when I have more time.

3. As a user, I want to like articles so I can revisit my favorites or see more similar content.

4. As a user, I want to share articles with others through social media or messaging platforms.

User Experience

  

Step-by-Step Flow

1. Onboarding (New Users)

â€¢ Users are prompted to select topics of interest during onboarding.

â€¢ Topics are presented as a visually engaging grid (e.g., â€œTech,â€ â€œSports,â€ â€œEntertainmentâ€).

â€¢ Users can select multiple topics or skip.

2. News Feed Personalization

â€¢ Based on selected topics, the news feed dynamically updates to show relevant content.

â€¢ Users can modify their topic preferences at any time via the settings menu.

3. Article Interaction (Engagement)

â€¢ Each article displays actionable buttons:

â€¢ Like: Adds the article to a â€œLikedâ€ section and improves future content suggestions.

â€¢ Bookmark: Saves the article to a â€œRead Laterâ€ section for easy access.

â€¢ Share: Opens sharing options (e.g., social media, email).

4. Dedicated Sections

â€¢ Liked: Displays a chronological list of all liked articles.

â€¢ Read Later: Shows all bookmarked articles.

â€¢ Shared: Optional tracking of articles the user has shared.

Narrative

  

Imagine Sarah, a tech enthusiast, downloads your app. During onboarding, she selects â€œTechâ€ and â€œEntertainmentâ€ as her preferred topics. Every day, Sarah receives a feed of news curated to her interests, including the latest iPhone announcements and movie trailers.

  

One morning, Sarah comes across an article about an iPhone software update. She bookmarks it to read during her lunch break. After reading, she shares it with her friends on WhatsApp. By liking the article, Sarah signals her interest in similar content, and her feed adapts over time to better reflect her preferences.

  

Sarahâ€™s experience keeps her engaged and returning to the app daily, knowing it saves her time and surfaces the news she cares about most.

Success Metrics

â€¢ Engagement: Increase in daily active users (DAUs) by 10% within 3 months.

â€¢ Retention: Increase 30-day retention rate by 20%.

â€¢ Feature Adoption:

â€¢ At least 60% of users selecting topics during onboarding.

â€¢ 50% of users bookmarking at least one article weekly.

â€¢ Sharing Activity: 25% of users sharing at least one article per week.

Technical Considerations

â€¢ Backend:

â€¢ Develop APIs for managing user preferences, bookmarks, likes, and shared articles.

â€¢ Ensure scalability for real-time updates to personalized feeds.

â€¢ Frontend:

â€¢ Intuitive UI for topic selection, bookmarks, and liked/shared sections.

â€¢ Use icons and clear labels for engagement actions (e.g., heart for Like, bookmark icon for Save).

â€¢ Analytics:

â€¢ Track engagement metrics (likes, bookmarks, shares) for user behavior insights.

â€¢ Use heatmaps or A/B testing to refine the topic selection flow.

â€¢ Data Privacy:

â€¢ Ensure compliance with GDPR/CCPA for user data related to preferences and sharing history.

Milestones & Sequencing

1. Week 1-4: Research & Design

â€¢ Finalize UI/UX for topic selection and engagement features.

â€¢ Define backend architecture and data models.

2. Week 5-8: Development Sprint 1

â€¢ Build topic selection flow and personalized feed backend.

â€¢ Develop basic bookmarking and liking functionality.

3. Week 9-12: Development Sprint 2

â€¢ Add sharing functionality and dedicated sections for Liked and Bookmarked content.

â€¢ Implement analytics and tracking.

4. Week 13-16: QA & Launch

â€¢ Comprehensive testing for bugs and usability issues.

â€¢ Soft launch to a beta group for feedback.

What do you think? Are there additional user needs or technical constraints I should consider?

## **Overview**

### **Primary Data Source**:

- **Bank Account**: The sole data source, reflecting deposits from all income streams related to the band.

### **Core Functionality**:

- Efficiently track and classify revenue to offer a clear understanding of the band’s financial health.

## **2. Functional Requirements**

### **2.1 Data Management**

**Normalization**:

- Convert transaction data into a consistent CSV format.
- Ensure data integrity and uniformity regardless of source format.

**Classification**:

- Categorize transactions into predefined categories:
    - **Band-Related Earnings**: Income directly related to the band’s operations, such as:
        - Live performances
        - Merchandise sales
        - Streaming royalties
        - Licensing fees
        - Additional subcategories to be defined through further research and discussion.
    - **Individual Earnings**: Income earned by band members from personal projects outside the band’s scope (e.g., Wes’s remote guitar sessions, Laurel’s demo singing).

With over a decade in product management and software engineering, I bring a proven record of delivering high-impact, data-driven products that drive user engagement and revenue growth. My background spans hands-on development to cross-functional leadership, enabling me to bridge technical strategy with business goals seamlessly.

**Product Growth That Drives Results**

My grandmother always said, “Results come first. Cookies come after dinner.”

Throughout my career, from starting as a lowly engineer at a struggling startup to leading product from multiple businesses, I have not wanted to resources, whether they be time, money, and energy. If we’re going to do something, it has to translate to value to both others (users) and ourselves (the business).

That’s why as Lead Product Manager and Software Engineer at Collab, I spearheaded initiatives, like the Business plan and collaboration features, that doubled revenue over two years, increased weekly engagement by 30% and decreased churn by 40%.

**Technical Leadership That Aligns Teams**

Building world-class products requires teamwork.

My technical foundation allows me to lead product development with a clear vision and drive alignment across engineering, design, marketing, and operations. For instance, my cross-functional focus enabled StreamYard to deliver features, including role-based access controls and AI-powered recommendations, that leveraged data-driven insights and met known and unknown customer needs.

**A Data-Driven Approach to Feature Prioritization**

I hate two things: onions and biased product decisions.

I witnessed and experienced enough failures to ensure that my decisions are grounded in insights, not assumptions, that come from cross-analyzing qualitative and quantitive data. Utilizing high-touch, such as daily user interviews, and low-touch, such as in-journey surveys, I can ensure that product work is focused on features that truly move the needle, resulting higher engagement and customer satisfaction.

Thank you for your time and consideration. Let’s chat soon about how to building products that resonate with users and advance your company’s mission by leveraging my expertise in high-value product innovation, strategic planning, and technical execution! 👋
